post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_47935616_47935713_0": {"length": 14, "quality": 0.875, "section_id": 7049}}, "n3337": {"so_47935616_47935713_0": {"length": 14, "quality": 0.875, "section_id": 6794}}, "n4659": {"so_47935616_47935713_0": {"length": 14, "quality": 0.875, "section_id": 8546}}}, "47935713": {"Id": "47935713", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>You're looking for [basic.scope.pdecl]:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_47935616_47935713_0\">The point of declaration for a name is immediately after its complete declarator (Clause 11) and before its initializer (if any), except as noted below.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So once it gets to the <code>=</code>, the definition of <code>foo</code> is complete (which is also a declaration) and it can be referred to in its own initializer.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2017-12-22T04:06:23.600", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2017-12-22T04:06:23.600", "ParentId": "47935616", "CommentCount": "3", "OwnerUserId": "5231607"}, "47935616": {"ViewCount": "79", "Body": "<p>The following program compiles and runs just fine.</p>\n<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;\n\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n    size_t foo = sizeof(foo);\n    cout &lt;&lt; foo &lt;&lt; endl;\n    return 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Using the compilation command</p>\n<pre><code>clang++ -o wut -Wall -Wextra -Werror -pedantic -ansi test.cc\n</code></pre>\n<p>I understand that this is <em>probably</em> the equivalent of</p>\n<pre><code>size_t foo;\nfoo = sizeof(foo);\n</code></pre>\n<p>Which makes more sense.</p>\n<p>However, the initial statement breaks my mind a bit since I think of the RHS being evaluated prior to the LHS (or overall statement) being executed - which in this case might suggest that <code>foo</code> doesn't yet exist.</p>\n<p>However, my assumption is that <code>size_t foo</code> always results in a declaration first, being broken out into its own statement during compile-time, followed by the definition.</p>\n<p>Is my assumption correct? Is this governed/well defined in the specification(s)? If so, which section(s)? I realize I compiled with <code>-ansi</code> but this appears to work, without error, on all standard versions I tried it with.</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "47935713", "Title": "Why does C++ allow you to reference a declared variable in the initial definition?", "CreationDate": "2017-12-22T03:50:08.990", "LastActivityDate": "2017-12-22T04:19:53.697", "CommentCount": "8", "LastEditDate": "2017-12-22T04:19:53.697", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "510036", "Id": "47935616", "Score": "-1", "OwnerUserId": "510036", "Tags": "<c++><standards>", "AnswerCount": "1"}});